\section{Background}

Drying of wet granular media has been widely studied in recent years. In a granular medium, the main phenomena taking place are illustrated in Fig. $2$a. Drying is widely considered as an invasion percolation process (IP)~\cite{Shaw87, Prat02}. It is a modified form of percolation, described by displacement of two immiscible fluids~\cite{Prat99}. Studies~\cite{Coussot00, Lehmann08, Shokri08, Yiotis12b, Yiotis12a, Prat02, Prat07, Chauvet09, Chauvet10} have shown distinct regimes associated with transport mechanisms that affect evaporation flux behavior in porous media. Water evaporation from porous media such as soil generally has two regimes and an abrupt transition from capillary-supported high and nearly constant rates (regime $1$) to diffusion-controlled lower evaporation rates (regime $2$)~\cite{Coussot00, Chauvet09, Prat07, Yiotis12a, Yiotis12b, Lehmann08}. During regime 1, the loss of water in the medium leads to liquid-gas interfaces that exhibit high capillary pressures, which permit liquid from the bulk to flow towards the evaporating surface located at the top of the tube. The films form the Partially Saturated Zone (PSZ). The interface between the lower fully wet region and the PSZ is called the percolating front. Its position is denoted as $z_{inf}$. This continuous hydraulic capillary network links the percolating front and the evaporating surface and liquid transport through this network helps sustain evaporation rates~\cite{Coussot00}. The mechanism taking place during regime 1 is illustrated in Fig. $2$a (left). As long as the liquid films are attached to the upper surface, evaporation rates remain high and the percolating front continues to recede inside the medium. The position of the percolating front, $z_{inf}$, scales linearly with time, $t$, during regime 1~\cite{Lehmann08, Shokri08, Yiotis12b, Prat02, Coussot00}. After the PSZ reaches a certain characteristic length, which depends on contact angle~\cite{Chraibi09, Shokri09} or pore shape~\cite{Prat07, Yiotis12b, Chauvet09}, the capillary connections are broken and thus liquid films detach from the evaporating surface and an evaporating front, $z_{sup}$ starts to form as shown in Fig. $2$a (right). This marks the onset of regime $2$ of evaporation. As the evaporating front also recedes inside the medium, a dry region separates the evaporating front and the surface of the tube. During regime 2, evaporation rates slow down and $z_{inf}$ scales as $\sqrt{t}$ because gaseous water now diffuses across the dry region to the  surface of the tube~\cite{Camassel05, Chauvet09, Yiotis12b}. 


