\abstract{
Understanding evaporation or drying in granular media still remains complex despite recent advancements. Evaporation depends on liquid transport across a connected film network from the bulk to the surface. In this study, we investigate the stability of film networks as a function of granular packing. Using a controlled experimental approach, we vary the granular packing geometry and show the changes in the height of the liquid film network during evaporation as packing shifts from a loose-packed to a close-packed arrangement. This height can be calculated from an equilibrium between hydrostatic pressure and the pressure difference between two points in the vertical film network. We use a simulation approach to calculate the pressure in both the percolating front and evaporating front within the two-phase zone of air/water mixture. Results show good agreement between the model and the experiment.}

\maketitle



Water evaporation out of porous media is a physical process of technological and scientific importance. In particular, it is known to affect mechanical and biological properties of soil. Thus, understanding its mechanism is of primary significance in hydrology~\cite{Lehmann08}. Previous studies~\cite{Lehmann08, Shokri08, Yiotis12b, Prat99} have tackled the challenge of predicting the evaporation rate and drying behavior out of a porous medium. More recent studies~\cite{Dreyfus14} have used evaporation rates to analytically predict the lifetime of plant. It is now well-established that the evaporation rate is intricately related to a so-called Partially Saturated Zone (PSZ), which is a mixture of air and liquid that forms beneath the surface. However, what affects the organization and geometrical characteristics of this layer is still under debate~\cite{Prat02, Prat07}. 

The mechanism of liquid flow through pores in the PSZ has been described by two models. In the first model, the transport of liquid through the PSZ is explained by the polydispersity of the pores. Pore size distribution is the key point that permits liquid flow from larger pores into smaller ones~\cite{Lehmann08, Shokri08}. In the second model, polydispersity is not a necessary ingredient. Individual pore size and shape is what governs the transport of liquid~\cite{Dong95, Chauvet09, Prat07, Chauvet10}. It has been shown both experimentally and numerically that corners within the pore walls help maintain the stability of the films~\cite{Chauvet09, Yiotis12b} and that the evaporation rate is influenced by sharp corner edges~\cite{Prat07, Dong95}. Films that carpet these corner edges act as hydraulic pathways for easy and rapid transport of water from the bulk out of the porous medium. Furthermore, it has been demonstrated that the evaporation mechanism out of a complex porous medium is perfectly analogous to the evaporation mechanism out of a square capillary tube, opening new routes towards a simplified and accurate description of evaporation~\cite{Prat07, Yiotis12b}.  The geometry of the corners of the square tube influence the curvature of the corner films, which could help disrupt or maintain liquid film stability~\cite{Yiotis12a, Yiotis12b}. This square tube model has been very useful for predicting evaporation rates~\cite{Camassel05, Chauvet09, Yiotis12a, Yiotis12b}. Still, to improve our understanding of the evaporation process, it is necessary to examine the stability of liquid films and its relation to granular packing geometry. 

In this paper, we study the evaporation out of a circular capillary tube filled with monodisperse glass beads. By changing the ratio between the tube diameter and the glass bead, we control the conformation of the beads in the tube from straight to close-packed. We show that packing configurations play a significant role in the stability of the liquid film network during evaporation and also contributes to transition from a capillary-supported to a diffusion-controlled regime. 



\section{\textcolor{black}{Materials and methods}}
Our experimental set-up consists of two types of capillary tubes and one type of glass spheres of diameter $d = 1.0 \pm 0.2$~mm (Sigma Aldrich, USA). The borosilicate capillary tubes have lengths of $L = 10$~cm (Vitrocom, NJ, USA), and is of circular cross-section. The tubes are filled with glass spheres to resemble a ``single-column" porous medium. Given a monodisperse set of glass spheres, two different internal diameters (1.5~mm, 2.0~mm) of the circular capillary tube are used to ensure specific packing configurations. The beads inside the circular tube form a 2D monolayer packing. We do not observe helical structures. The tube walls are made hydrophobic using a silane solution (OMS Solutions, Canada) to reduce wetting effects on the capillary tube wall. 

The columns are vertically mounted on a stand and  the top area remains open. They are fully saturated with deionized water using a vacuum pump. This technique eliminates the presence of bubbles. The glass spheres, pre-washed with 0.1~M HCl, have a constant wetting angle $\theta = 16.7^{\circ} \pm 4.5^{\circ}$. The spheres are placed in the capillary tubes in different packing configurations defined by the packing angle $\alpha$, as depicted in Fig. $1$a-c. Straight configurations have a packing angle of $\alpha = 180^{\circ}$, while loose configurations have angles of $60^{\circ} < \alpha \leq 180^{\circ}$, and close-packed configurations have angles of $\alpha = 60^{\circ}$. 

The experimental porosities, $\phi_A$, are calculated from the volume of the capillary tube, $V_C$, and total number of glass spheres, $nV_S$: $\phi_A = (V_C - nV_S) / V_C$, where $V_S$ is the volume of a single glass bead and $n$ is the total number of glass beads inside the capillary tube. In Fig. $1$d, the porosities are plotted as a function of packing angle, $\alpha$. The value of $\alpha$ is the average value of angle measurements of the beads positioned inside the tube. The theoretical porosities are calculated from the geometry of three adjacent spherical particles, shown below:

