First, $P_{sup}$ is the pressure at the top of the liquid column (evaporating front). This pressure is minimal when the meniscus adopts the smaller curvature that can still join three beads as shown in meniscus ``I" in Fig. 4d. To estimate this pressure we focus on the pressure in a single pendular bridge. We consider a drop of water of certain volume trapped between two adjacent spheres as shown in Fig. $5$a. During evaporation, the volume of liquid in the pendular bridge decreases (Fig. 5a) and the pressure is defined as $\bigtriangleup P = \sigma (-1/r_1 + 1/r_2 )$. Relative to the surrounding ambient pressure, the liquid capillary bridges have very low pressure (increasingly negative), which allow it to draw liquid from other neighbors~\cite{Xu08}. 

Second, $P_{inf}$ is the pressure in the bottom of the PSZ (percolating front). During evaporation, the saturation of water at the percolating front is higher compared to the saturation of water at the evaporating front. One can consider the meniscus in the percolation front to have the shape presented in Fig. 5b (left panel). Therefore, to estimate this pressure, we focus on the pressure in the pendular bridge between three adjacent spheres. Here, at constant liquid volume, the shape of the meniscus depends on the half-separation distance, $s$, between the spheres, which changes with the packing angle, $\alpha$. Fig. 5b (right panel) shows the change in meniscus shape as a function of packing angle. In this figure, increasing liquid volume also increases the value of the bridge angle or half-filling angle, $\beta$, until liquid film continuity is recovered. Thus, the minimum value of the bridge angle to maintain liquid continuity is $\beta = \alpha / 2$ . Tomography data have also shown that the liquid bridges in a dense packing of equally sized spheres, $\alpha \sim 60^{\circ}$, will also achieve coalescence if the bridge angle $\beta = 30^{\circ}$~\cite{Scheel08}.

Having qualitatively described the forms of the meniscus in the upper and lower parts of the PSZ, we now quantitatively define the pressures in both areas.

