Each curve in Fig. 6c is shown at constant meniscus volume. Hence, in Fig. 6c, the higher curves on the graph show larger meniscus volume. We obtain no numerical solution for $\alpha > 120^{\circ}$. We use a polynomial fit to interpolate the simulation points and demonstrate the dependence of the pressure difference with packing angle inside the percolating front. 

In both the evaporating front $P_{sup}$ and the percolating front $P_{inf}$, the pressure is calculated as the difference between the surrounding air and the pressure in the liquid. Once the values of $P_{inf}$ and $P_{sup}$ have been determined, we use Eq. 2 to calculate the values of height $h$ of the PSZ as a function of packing angle, $h = f(\alpha)$.

As the volume in the meniscus that joins three spheres in the percolation front is unknown, we use it as a fitting parameter. We find that the best fit is achieved for $V_{sim} = 0.5$. In applying Eq. 2, we find numerically that above a certain packing angle ($\sim 70^{\circ}$), the pressure in the evaporating front gets larger than the pressure in the percolating front, $P_{sup} > P_{inf}$, and thus $h < 0$. A negative value for $h$ is physically impossible and is interpretated as a condition when the liquid film network is not stable anymore and thus cannot exist continuously. Therefore above a critical angle, when the model predicts a negative $h$ value, all values of $h$ are instead represented as $h=0$. This ``critical" angle was also observed  in our experiments, where no PSZ is formed and only the diffusive regime appears. The model is compared to our experimental results, as presented in Fig. 7, and shows an excellent agreement. 




