\section{Conclusion}

We studied how granular packing affects liquid film stability in capillary networks by using spherical particles inside circular capillary tubes to demonstrate a simple granular system with varying packing arrangements from loose-packed to close-packed. We compared our experimental results with simulation performed using Surface Evolver. Using simple geometrical argument, we were able to calculate the pressure in the evaporation and percolation fronts and extract the height of the PSZ from these values. Close-packed systems have more stable liquid film connections; thus, evaporation rates are faster.  At a certain packing threshold, liquid connections are broken and thus loose-packed systems have less stable liquid films that easily break and have slower evaporation rates (via diffusion). 

The manner in which the particles are arranged in 3D bulk systems clearly affects packing compactness and liquid distribution. Less liquid will be found in densely and closely-packed areas where evaporation is favored while, in contrast, loosely-packed areas will hold greater liquid content for longer periods. Results also raise interesting questions on the role of polydispersity on packing compactness especially when smaller particles fill the pore spaces made by surrounding larger ones. Such configurations create smaller pores, whose liquid films have smaller curvatures and high pressures. This drives greater capillary flow for rapid transport of water. Such results would help contribute to the better comprehension of the complex nature of multiphase fluid flow in 3D bulk systems. 






