Liquid inside the tubes are left for evaporation. Typical evaporation patterns can be seen in Fig. 2b, which shows different images at various stages of evaporation. We can see different behaviors depending on the packing configuration. For straight configuration or high packing angle, there is no formation of PSZ (Fig. 2b, left). This behavior is observed until the packing angle is decreased down to  $ \alpha \sim 100^{\circ}$ (Fig. 2b, middle), where films subsist in the PSZ. When the packing angle is again further decreased to a close-packed configuration, a large PSZ appears: the evaporation behavior is now completely analogous to that of a 2D packing. To quantify the differences in evaporation behavior for each packing configuration, we measure the position of the percolating front with time as shown in Fig. 3a. The curves in the figure are numbered according to configuration encoded on the legend bar, whose corresponding packing angle values are shown in Table 1. 

Fig. 3a also shows a strong difference in the behavior of the front when the packing angle, $\alpha$, is increased from close-packed configurations to loose configurations. Close-packed configurations (1-3) clearly show a fast-developing first regime prior to an abrupt transition towards the slow second regime of evaporation. For loose configurations (4-9), the position of the percolating increases at a very slow rate. There is no observable first regime. The time-evolution of the front position suggests a purely diffusive regime with time scaling as $\sqrt{t}$~\cite{Camassel05, Bird02} (solid line). This same observation is inferred by looking at the extents of the height of the PSZ, $h$, as a function of time, in Fig. $3$b. For loose and straight configurations (4-9), the PSZ seems unstable and $h$ heavily fluctuates around 1 or 2 bead diameters (0.1-0.2~cm). The upper front of the PSZ disconnects immediately from the evaporating surface. This observation confirms the fact that there is no regime 1 for loose and straight configurations, but the system is instantly dominated by the slow regime $2$ of diffusion. Measurements of $h$ for close configuration clearly show two distinct regimes in Fig. 3b (1-3). For close configurations, $h$ reaches a maximum value before stabilization at a quasi-constant value. To summarize, these experiments show that evaporation of a single tube of spheres in a predefined controlled arrangement exhibit the same characteristic as the evaporation of a 2D system. However, the arrangement of the glass bead controls the extent of the PSZ. Above a certain configuration angle, the PSZ cannot form, the evaporation pattern is analogous to that of almost perfectly circular tube (solid black line in Fig. 3a). 


The process is modelled and described schematically in Fig. 4. The initial configuration is depicted in Fig. 4a, where a fully saturated tube with beads is shown. As water evaporates, the volume decreases (Fig. 4b).  Air continues to penetrate inside the medium and the menisci form between spherical beads 1, 2, and 3 in Fig. 4c. ``I" and ``II" are the menisci between beads 1 and 2 and beads 2 and 3 respectively. At the beginning of the process, menisci ``I" and ``II" are linked, water from one meniscus can flow into the other. As the process goes on, Fig. 4c, more menisci develop along the tortuous packing and a column of water forms the PSZ. At the top of the column, however, volume of the meniscus ``I" gets smaller and smaller until it reaches a volume where the connection between ``I" and ``II" break (Fig. 4d). After prolonged periods, this connection is completely disconnected (Fig. 4e). This description helps understand why close-packings allow for larger PSZ heights. Indeed as packing gets closer, menisci of higher curvatures are formed that still ensure hydraulic connectivity with the menisci formed below in the PSZ. Higher curvatures induce higher pressure drops along the columns and therefore lead to larger PSZ~\cite{Scheel08}.





\subsection{Model Definition of the Extent of the Liquid Film Region}


For a certain height $h$, the difference in pressure along the interfaces of the menisci in the percolating and evaporating fronts of the liquid film region is in equilibrium with the hydrostatic pressure~\cite{Princen69, deGennes10}. Liquid flow upward towards the tube top is driven by a competition between capillary, viscous, and gravity forces. The Bond number, $B_o = \frac{\rho g R^{2}}{\sigma}$, where $R$ is the bead radius and $\sigma$ is the surface tension of water, gives $B_o \sim 10^{-3}$. Thus, capillary forces dominate over gravity. The capillary number is defined as, $C_a = \frac{\eta \nu}{\sigma}$, where $\eta$ is the dynamic viscosity and $\nu$ is the characteristic liquid velocity determined experimentally from the curves of $h = f(t)$. We calculate $C_a \sim 10^{-9}$. Thus, capillary forces dominate over viscous forces. Thus, for this particular simplified set-up of a granular column of beads inside a circular tube, viscous effects are ignored. In addition, surface tension gradients are also neglected because temperature inside the controlled environment chamber is constant. 

The height, $h$ of the PSZ is then written as:
